CKA Mock Questions: Pod Admission and Scheduling

Below are 10 task-style questions modeled on the CKA exam format, covering resource limits, node affinity, taints/tolerations, topology spread, priority classes, and admission controls. Each includes a worked solution.

Question 1: Resource Requests and Limits

Task: Create a Pod named resource-pod in the namespace scheduling using the image nginx:1.25. The container must request 250m CPU and 128Mi memory, with limits of 500m CPU and 256Mi memory.

Solution:

``yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: resource-pod
  namespace: scheduling
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx:1.25
    resources:
      requests:
        cpu: "250m"
        memory: "128Mi"
      limits:
        cpu: "500m"
        memory: "256Mi"
`

Apply with kubectl apply -f resource-pod.yaml. Verify with kubectl describe pod resource-pod -n scheduling | grep -A4 Limits.

Question 2: Node Selector

Task: Label node worker-1 with disktype=ssd. Then schedule a Pod named ssd-pod using image redis:7 that runs only on nodes with that label using nodeSelector.

Solution:

`bash
kubectl label node worker-1 disktype=ssd
`

`yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: ssd-pod
spec:
  nodeSelector:
    disktype: ssd
  containers:
  - name: redis
    image: redis:7
`

Verify: kubectl get pod ssd-pod -o wide — it should land on worker-1.

Question 3: Required Node Affinity

Task: Create a Pod named affinity-pod using image busybox (with sleep 3600) that must run on a node where the label zone equals either us-east-1a or us-east-1b.

Solution:

`yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: affinity-pod
spec:
  affinity:
    nodeAffinity:
      requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
        nodeSelectorTerms:
        - matchExpressions:
          - key: zone
            operator: In
            values:
            - us-east-1a
            - us-east-1b
  containers:
  - name: busybox
    image: busybox
    command: ["sh", "-c", "sleep 3600"]
`

Key points: requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution is a hard rule; the Pod stays Pending if no node matches.

Question 4: Preferred Node Affinity with Weight

Task: Schedule a Deployment named web (3 replicas, image nginx) that prefers nodes labeled tier=frontend with weight 80, but can run elsewhere if needed.

Solution:

`yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: web
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: web
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: web
    spec:
      affinity:
        nodeAffinity:
          preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
          - weight: 80
            preference:
              matchExpressions:
              - key: tier
                operator: In
                values:
                - frontend
      containers:
      - name: nginx
        image: nginx
`

Weight ranges from 1–100; higher weights score nodes higher during the scoring phase of scheduling.

Question 5: Taints and Tolerations

Task: Taint node worker-2 with dedicated=gpu:NoSchedule. Then create a Pod named gpu-workload using image tensorflow/tensorflow that tolerates this taint.

Solution:

`bash
kubectl taint node worker-2 dedicated=gpu:NoSchedule
`

`yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: gpu-workload
spec:
  tolerations:
  - key: "dedicated"
    operator: "Equal"
    value: "gpu"
    effect: "NoSchedule"
  containers:
  - name: tf
    image: tensorflow/tensorflow
`

Remove the taint later with kubectl taint node worker-2 dedicated=gpu:NoSchedule- (note the trailing -).

Question 6: Pod Anti-Affinity

Task: Create a Deployment cache with 3 replicas of redis:7, ensuring no two replicas run on the same node (use Pod anti-affinity with the kubernetes.io/hostname topology key).

Solution:

`yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: cache
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: cache
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: cache
    spec:
      affinity:
        podAntiAffinity:
          requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
          - labelSelector:
              matchExpressions:
              - key: app
                operator: In
                values:
                - cache
            topologyKey: kubernetes.io/hostname
      containers:
      - name: redis
        image: redis:7
`

If the cluster has fewer than 3 nodes, one replica will remain Pending — expected behavior.

Question 7: Topology Spread Constraints

Task: Create a Deployment frontend with 6 replicas of nginx. Spread the Pods evenly across zones (label topology.kubernetes.io/zone) with a maximum skew of 1.

Solution:

`yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: frontend
spec:
  replicas: 6
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: frontend
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: frontend
    spec:
      topologySpreadConstraints:
      - maxSkew: 1
        topologyKey: topology.kubernetes.io/zone
        whenUnsatisfiable: DoNotSchedule
        labelSelector:
          matchLabels:
            app: frontend
      containers:
      - name: nginx
        image: nginx
`

whenUnsatisfiable: DoNotSchedule makes the constraint hard; use ScheduleAnyway for a soft preference.

Question 8: PriorityClass

Task: Create a PriorityClass named high-priority with value 1000000 and description "Critical workloads". Then create a Pod critical-app using image nginx that uses this PriorityClass.

Solution:

`yaml
apiVersion: scheduling.k8s.io/v1
kind: PriorityClass
metadata:
  name: high-priority
value: 1000000
globalDefault: false
description: "Critical workloads"

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: critical-app
spec:
  priorityClassName: high-priority
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx
`

Higher-priority Pods can preempt lower-priority ones if the scheduler cannot find space. Verify with kubectl get priorityclass.

Question 9: Cordon, Drain, and Uncordon

Task: Mark node worker-3 unschedulable, evict all workloads (ignoring DaemonSets and tolerating emptyDir data loss), then return it to service.

Solution:

`bash
Mark unschedulable (no new pods)
kubectl cordon worker-3

Evict existing pods
kubectl drain worker-3 --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data

Return to service
kubectl uncordon worker-3
`

cordon only blocks new scheduling; drain evicts running Pods. Add --force if there are bare Pods (not managed by a controller).

Question 10: LimitRange for Namespace Defaults

Task: In namespace dev, create a LimitRange named dev-limits that sets a default container request of 100m/128Mi and a default limit of 500m/512Mi. Verify by creating a Pod without explicit resources and confirming the defaults were applied.

Solution:

`yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: LimitRange
metadata:
  name: dev-limits
  namespace: dev
spec:
  limits:
  - type: Container
    default:
      cpu: "500m"
      memory: "512Mi"
    defaultRequest:
      cpu: "100m"
      memory: "128Mi"
`

Test it:

`bash
kubectl run test --image=nginx -n dev
kubectl describe pod test -n dev | grep -A6 Limits
`

You should see the LimitRange defaults applied to the container's Requests and Limits, even though they weren't specified in the Pod spec.

Quick Reference: Affinity Operators

| Operator | Meaning |
|----------|---------|
| In | Label value is in the supplied set |
| NotIn | Label value is not in the set |
| Exists | Label key exists (any value) |
| DoesNotExist | Label key is absent |
| Gt / Lt | Numeric greater/less than (node affinity only) |

A solid exam strategy: always verify scheduling outcomes with kubectl get pods -o wide and check kubectl describe pod <name> for events when a Pod stays Pending` — the scheduler explains exactly which predicate failed.
